tSuy fnmilh pf-75569bed">What is NAD?</span></h3><p data-pf-type="Paragraph2" class="sc-pkvvt cbrLgP pf-232b7233"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-ptSuy fnmilh pf-30d7232b"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) is found in all living cells.</span><br></span></p><p data-pf-type="Paragraph2" class="sc-pkvvt cbrLgP pf-a251456b"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-ptSuy fnmilh pf-3a25a251">It’s a central mediator of cellular energy metabolism and a crucial link between nutritional intake, cellular metabolism and health.
<br>NAD exists in two forms: an oxidized and reduced form, abbreviated as NAD+ and NADH respectively. Our NMN supplement converts into NAD+.
<br>NAD was discovered over a hundred years ago by scientists studying fermentation. Recently it has been hailed as a super-centenarian molecule. This is because its role in the biological process of ageing is being recognized.  NAD levels have been shown to decline during chronological ageing and this decline is both a consequence of the ageing process and also a contributor to the development of age-related cellular dysfunction.&nbsp;<br></span></p></div></div></div><div class="sc-qPjXN eYzxUD pf-539de456 pf-r pf-r-align--cm" data-pf-type="Row" style="--pf-s-lg:0px; --pf-s-md:0px; --pf-s-sm:0px; --pf-s-xs:15px;"><div class="sc-pbYdQ jklmHY pf-c pf-c-xs--12 pf-c-sm--4 pf-c-md--4 pf-c-lg--6"><div class="sc-pkUyL fTyjzF pf-aff28405" data-pf-type="Column"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-oTLFK lcHmGL pf-7328f145"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-ptSuy fnmilh pf-310e7328">What is NMN? </span></h3><p data-pf-type="Paragraph2" class="sc-pkvvt cbrLgP pf-9a9aaff2"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-ptSuy fnmilh pf-91ed9a9a"> As our bodies can’t absorb NAD+ directly we need to use a “precursor”. One of the precursors for NAD+ is nicotinamide mononucleotide, which is commonly known as NMN. NMN is a Vitamin B3 (niacin) derivative. Put simply, NMN increases NAD, activates sirtuins and suppresses ageing.<br>NMN has gained a lot of attention recently, especially after the release of longevity scientist, David Sinclair’s book Lifespan. In his book, the scientist discusses his research examining NMN, particularly in mice.<br></span></p></div></div><div class="sc-pbYdQ jklmHY pf-c pf-c-xs--12 pf-c-sm--8 pf-c-md--8 pf-c-lg--4"><div class="sc-pkUyL fTyjzF pf-f241539d" data-pf-type="Column"><img sizes="(min-width: 992px) 1200px, (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 991px) 800px, 400px" srcset="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0461/5222/0837/t/4/assets/pf-2ccab6ad--mice.jpeg?v=1608136861 1200w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0461/5222/0837/t/4/assets/pf-2ccab6ad--mice_800x800